  "text": "Telangiectasias are small dilated blood vessels that develop in a small proportion of patients taking EGFR inhibitors, generally appearing on the face, chest, back, and limbs. Hyperpigmentation may result from fading telangiectasias [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] or as a consequence of inflammation. Because telangiectasias and hyperpigmentation usually occur as a result of photosensitivity, patients being treated with an EGFR inhibitor should be counseled to practice sun protection. The Canadian Dermatology Association has outlined sun protection for the general population, which includes wearing an SPF 30 broad-spectrum sunscreen, scheduling outdoor activities before 11 am and after 4 pm, and wearing appropriate clothing to cover the skin, including hat. Darker-skinned individuals, in particular, are susceptible to hyperpigmentation 24,43,59,60,68,69 .",
